body.description: Travel in style with the SwissGear 7366 Expandable Hardside Luggage Set. Both modern and utilitarian, its lustrous metal zippers and rugged construction exemplify its long-lasting quality. The set contains the 19” Carry-On, 23” and a 27" Expandable Hardside Luggage. Its almost indestructible split case opens to display the main compartment equipped with tie-down clothing straps, a roomy zippered lid pocket, and a large zippered packing pocket to keep your travel-sized essentials separate from your clothes. It also includes a premium steel locking handle, four 360-degree wheels, expandable packing space, and a molded grab handle. Guaranteeing extra security with its built-in TSA-approved three-dial combination lock, make this a go-to for your upcoming voyage because, whether traveling for business or pleasure, this is doing adventure the right way.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on February 3, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Gorgeous AND works better than any of my previous luggage
reviews.reviewText: First off, I read other reviews about this bag missing the cup holder - it's important to READ the description closely before ordering. The detail page clearly states the cup holder is only on the small bag (carry-on), not on the medium or large size. The tag that comes with the luggage says the exact same thing, I'm uploading a photo of it. On a check-in bag you rarely need a cup holder anyway, as you check it in as soon as you get to the airport. It'd also be another thing to break when handled by the airport employees.This is an absolutely beautiful bag. I have always used the 28-29" sized luggage bags for check-ins, but on my last trip to Europe I realized just how big and clumpsy it was to move around. So when one of the wheels broke on my then American Tourister Bon Air Spinner and I went looking for a new bag, I decided to go with this Swiss Gear in the 23" size instead. I LOVE the looks on this one, which was one of the main pros for me, it also comes in awesome colors that will be very visible at the baggage claim. And yes, even if it's significantly smaller than my previous 28" and I won't fit nearly as much in it, it will be so much easier to store, roll around, fit on the train, in the car, the taxi etc - just easier to travel with in general. I just have to learn to not bring as many gifts to my family. This Swiss Gear is expandable, something my previous bag wasn't, so that will help as well.It is extremely light weight!It rolls like a dream even when packaged with 45lb of stuff, much better than than my American Tourister. Same goes for the zippers, they're smooth like butter! The handle and "button" are also better than what I'm used to on previous luggage, there are no "hiccups", it's smooth, stable and very exact in its locking mechanism. No way to know how long it'll be this great, but for now I'm super happy with it.The only thing I'm missing are a couple of zippered pockets on the interior zippered "lid" between the two compartments. I had that on my previous bag and it was so convenient for smaller, flatter items. It's a minor thing so it won't affect the rating, this is definitely a 5 star luggage - and the price range is great too.

reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Survived my tip to Vegas
reviews.reviewText: I had my previous suitcase for over 10 years and was forced to get a new one. I love the lavender color on this one because it is easy to spot at the airport. reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on October 2, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars A particular downside…
reviews.reviewText: I like this suitcase a lot. It’s attractive, well sized for most airlines, the zippered side helps you organize loose objects in your bag without dumping them all over the place while zipping, and the lock has the capability to add a backup lock—which I didn’t use but did appreciate.I bought this item a couple of months before I would need it knowing that in one month I’d have to fly 17 times. When I bought it I didn’t think much about the cup holder—who cares, right? But after a few five hour layovers I thought about it a LOT. It’s a really handy feature to have in certain circumstances, but it also manages to be the biggest downside. The cup holder is NOT standard sized. It’s exactly 2 and 1/8th inches across, making it great for a plastic water bottle but quite small for most travel mugs/tumblers/cups. I even struggled with a standard paper coffee cup (think large Starbucks cup) which was left hovering above the (disconnected) base support.In short: a great carry on. Awesome if you’re basically living out of it. You’ll come to be annoyed by the cup holder sooner or later, and hopefully my included measurement will help you find a cup that works for you.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on April 12, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 4.0 out of 5 stars Good not great
reviews.reviewText: Nice bag that I have some durability concerns with. The bag would be great for a normal person that travels a couple of times a year. It's a well" designed holds a ton of stuff. It will expand if needed. I regularly load up 40-50 pds in it. Problem is I fly a couple times at least each week and I fear that it may not be durable enough, especially handle, to survive the pounding I subject any bag too. Telescoping handle has too much flex when pushing bag and will probably be fist failure point. Still a really great bag for normal travelers just might not be robust enough for 100 flights a year. Hopefully I'm wrong!
